}

{
  "complexity_details": "The activity presents significant technical and institutional complexity. It requires developing National Inventory Reports (NIRs) for 1990-2022 and 1990-2024, strictly adhering to new MPGs (Decision 18/CMA.1) and the 2019 Refinement to the 2006 IPCC Guidelines, a significant shift from previous reports that used mainly Tier 1 methodologies with low quality assurance. There are noted gaps in data consistency, human capacities, and coordination among data providers, requiring extensive data collection, recalculation, and capacity building. A crucial aspect is operationalizing an existing but non-operational Measurement, Reporting, and Verification (MRV) system, including a climate finance module. Furthermore, integrating gender equity considerations and sex-disaggregated data into NDC analysis and MRV systems is a new and complex requirement, moving from a baseline of \"no inclusion\" to \"partial inclusion.\"",
  "how_integrated_description": "This activity is an Enabling Activity project, highly integrated and cohesive within Bosnia and Herzegovina's broader climate change governance framework and international reporting obligations. It is not a standalone larger program but a crucial component designed to fulfill commitments under the UNFCCC and the Paris Agreement. The project leverages existing institutional and analytical capacities built over two decades through previous National Communication Projects and the ongoing Capacity Building Initiative on Transparency (CBIT) project, which it explicitly states it \"fully complements.\" It aligns with the GEF-8 Climate Change Focal Area Strategy and contributes to national sustainable development goals (SDG 13), ensuring BiH meets critical reporting obligations and integrates climate change into its development framework. Synergies will be built with other ongoing development projects."
}

{
  "complexity_details": "The activity faced high complexity due to addressing the core problem of unsustainable commercial forest management in the Congo Basin within a difficult and dynamic environment. It involved diverse technical initiatives such as training for reduced-impact logging, ecological research, wildlife management, and digital tool development. Ambitious targets, like certifying 10 million hectares, were deemed challenging from the outset due to declining demand for certified timber and market conditions. Social complexities included considering the needs of Pygmies and other vulnerable groups regarding hunting rights and non-wood product access. Initial assumptions in the project design were also found to be incorrect, further contributing to the complexity.",
  "how_integrated_description": "This activity, \"Förderung zertifizierter Waldbewirtschaftung,\" is not considered a larger program itself but is directly and cohesively integrated into a broader joint program, referred to as a \"joint programme\" or \"broader joint program.\" It is designed with complementary Technical Cooperation (TC) and Financial Cooperation (FC) measures within this larger framework. Institutional strengthening, while not a direct part of this specific Financial Cooperation activity, was planned as part of the overarching joint program."
}

{
